1x8.title: Bayes's Rule (odds form):        Intro (Math 2)
1x8.clickbait: Intro to the odds form of Bayes's Rule, for people who can think in algebra
1x8.text:
In the [1ts previous part of this introduction], we translated the Diseasitis word problem:

> 20% of the patients in the screening population start out with Diseasitis. Among patients with Diseasitis, 90% turn the tongue depressor black. 30% of the patients without Diseasitis will also turn the tongue depressor black. Among all the patients with black tongue depressors, how many have Diseasitis?

Into the calculation:

$(2 : 8) \times (9 : 3) \ = \ (1 : 4) \times (3 : 1) \ = \ (3 : 4),$ corresponding to a 3/7 probability.

We will now generalize this rule.

# Odds ratios

In general, ratios $(x : y)$ express *relative* quantities.  Saying "There's 1 sick tree for every 3 healthy trees" expresses the same idea as "There's 2 sick trees for every 6 healthy trees."  If the original odds ratio is $(x : y)$ we can multiply by a positive number $\alpha$ and get an equivalent odds ratio $(\alpha x : \alpha y).$ 

If there's 2 sick trees for every 3 healthy trees, and every tree is either sick or healthy, then the *probability* of randomly picking a sick tree from among *all* trees is 2/(2+3):

![](https://i.imgur.com/GVZnz2c.png?0)

In general, we can convert a relative odds ratio like $(a : b : c)$ to the probabilities $(\frac{a}{a + b + c} : \frac{b}{a + b + c} : \frac{c}{a + b + c}).$  If the set of possibilities $A, B, C$ are [1rd mutually exclusive and exhaustive], then the probabilities $\mathbb P(A) + \mathbb P(B) + \mathbb P(C)$ should sum to $1.$  The process of dividing each term by the sum of terms, to turn a set of proportional odds into probabilities that sum to 1, is called [1rk normalization].

# Relative likelihoods

If we consider the waterfall visualization...

![](https://i.imgur.com/eQh2qUt.png?0)

...then we see that the *proportion* of red vs. blue water at the bottom will be the same whether there's 200 vs. 800 gallons per second of red vs. blue water at the top of the waterfall, or 20,000 vs. 80,000 gallons/sec.  This means that the relative odds ratio (1 : 4) is a good way to express what's happening at the top of the waterfall.

Similarly, 45% and 15% of the red and blue water making it to the bottom, would give the same *relative proportion* of red and blue water in the bottom pool, as 90% and 30%.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    

![](https://i.imgur.com/6FOndjc.png?0)

This is what justified our taking in the data that 90% of sick patients and 30% of healthy patients would get positive test results (a black tongue depressor), and summarizing this as the *likelihood ratio* (3 : 1), which would have been the same ratio if 45% of sick patients and 15% of healthy patients got positive test results.

We will later identify the likelihood ratio with the concept of [bayes_strength_of_evidence the strength of evidence].

# Bayes's Rule

We are now ready to state the odds form of Bayes's Rule:

$\textbf{Prior odds} \times \textbf{Likelihood ratio} = \textbf{Posterior odds}$

The [1rm prior] odds refer to the relative proportion of red vs. blue water at the top of the waterfall, or the prior odds a patient is sick before seeing any test results.

The [1rq] refers to how much more likely each sick patient is to get a positive test result than each healthy patient.

The [1rp posterior] odds are the relative proportions of red vs. blue water at the bottom of the waterfall, or the relative proportion of sick vs. healthy patients among all patients with positive test results.  In this case, 3 : 4.

![labeled waterfall](https://i.imgur.com/CXsoZhA.png?0)

# Formal statement

In logic, if $X$ and $Y$ are propositions, then $X \wedge Y$ denotes the proposition that both X and Y are true.  Thus, $\mathbb P(X \wedge Y)$ denotes "The probability that $X$ and $Y$ are both true.

We now define a new concept, "conditional probability":

$\mathbb P(X|Y) = \dfrac{\mathbb P(X \wedge Y)}{\mathbb P(Y)}$

We pronounce $\mathbb P(X|Y)$ as "the conditional probability of X, given Y".  Intuitively, this is supposed to mean "The probability that $X$ is true, *assuming* that proposition $Y$ is true".  $\mathbb P(sick|positive),$ meaning "The probability that a patient is sick given that they get a positive test result", is calculated by taking the 18 patients who are sick *and* have positive test results, and dividing by all 42 of the patients who got positive test results.  That is, $\mathbb P(sick|positive) = \frac{\mathbb P(sick \wedge positive)}{\mathbb P(positive)}.$

![diseasitis frequency](https://i.imgur.com/0XDbrYi.png?0)

![bag of 18 and 24 patients](https://i.imgur.com/W6avfHO.png?0)

We could say that the "given" operator in $\mathbb P(X|Y)$ tells us to assume that $Y$ is true, to restrict our attention to only possible universes where $Y$ is true, and then ask about the probability of $X$ *within* those universes.

Similarly, if out of 100 patients, 20 have Diseasitis and 18 of those 20 will have positive test results (*and* Diseasitis), then $\mathbb P(positive|sick) = \frac{\mathbb P(sick \wedge positive)}{\mathbb P(sick)} = \frac{18}{20} = 0.9$ or 90%.  Note that $\mathbb P(X|Y) \neq \mathbb P(Y|X),$ which is unfortunately the source of a lot of practical errors when you're trying to do these calculations using only the formal notation, at least until you get used to it.  Worse, the '|' is a symmetrical symbol, but that's unfortunately the standard.

So again, in $\mathbb P(\cdot|\cdot)$, the thing we're assuming is true is on the right side, the thing we're inferring from that is on the left side.

The calculation we did earlier corresponds to claiming:

$\dfrac{\mathbb P(sick|positive)}{\mathbb P(\neg sick|positive)} = \dfrac{\mathbb P(positive|sick)}{\mathbb P(positive|\neg sick)} \cdot \dfrac{\mathbb P(sick)}{\mathbb P(\neg sick)}$

Since every patient is either sick or healthy, and this includes "every patient with positive test results", we're justified in demanding that $\mathbb P(sick|positive) + \mathbb P(\neg sick|positive) = 1.$  Maintaining the ratio of 3 : 4, we end up with probabilities of 3/7 and 4/7.

In general, for every pair of hypotheses $H_i$ and $H_j$ and piece of evidence $e$, Bayes's Rule in the relative-odds form states:

$
\dfrac{\mathbb P(H_i)}{\mathbb P(H_j)}
\cdot 
\dfrac{\mathbb P(e|H_i)}{\mathbb P(e|H_j)} 
= 
\dfrac{\mathbb P(H_i|e)}{\mathbb P(H_j|e)}
$

We can now [1xr prove Bayes's Rule] by repeatedly applying the definition of [1rj conditional probability]:

$
\dfrac{\mathbb P(H_i)}{\mathbb P(H_j)} \times  \dfrac{\mathbb P(e|H_i)}{\mathbb P(e|H_j)}
= \dfrac{\mathbb P(e \wedge H_i)}{\mathbb P(e \wedge H_j)}
= \dfrac{\mathbb P(e \wedge H_i) / \mathbb P(e)}{\mathbb P(e \wedge H_j) / \mathbb P(e)}
= \dfrac{\mathbb P(H_i|e)}{\mathbb P(H_j|e)}
$

In the Diseasitis problem, these quantities would be:

$\dfrac{20\%}{80\%} \times  \dfrac{90\%}{30\%} = \dfrac{18\%}{24\%} = \dfrac{0.18 / 0.42}{0.24 / 0.42} = \dfrac{43\%}{57\%}$

Graphical representation:

![bayes venn](https://i.imgur.com/YBc2nYo.png?0)

# Further example: Widget problem

We previously had the problem:

> 10% of widgets are bad and 90% are good. 4% of good widgets emit sparks, and 12% of bad widgets emit sparks. Can you calculate in your head what percentage of sparking widgets are bad?

The prior odds are 1 : 9 for bad widgets vs. good widgets.

12% of bad widgets and 4% of good widgets emit sparks, so that's a likelihood ratio of 3 : 1 for sparking (bad widgets are 3 times as likely to emit sparks).

$(1 : 9 ) \times (3 : 1)  \ = \ (3 : 9) \ \cong \ (1 : 3)$ posterior odds for bad vs. good sparking widgets.  So 1/4 of sparking widgets are bad.

Knowing about the relative-odds trick can be a good deal simpler than trying to multiply percentages in your head.

## Interpretation

Also at this point, we can start to build up an intuition for [bayes_claims_and_evidence the burden of prior improbability versus the strength of evidence].

Bad widgets started out relatively rare:  1 in 10.  We applied a test, looking for sparks, that was only 3 times as likely to label bad widgets as to label good widgets; *the evidence was weaker than the prior improbability of the claim.*

This doesn't mean we toss out the evidence and ignore it.  It does mean that, after updating on the observation of sparkiness, we only gave 25% posterior credence to the widget being bad - the probability didn't go over 50%.
